name.text: Set Operations and Cardinality Calculations in Set Theory

questiontext.text:
\(\mathscr{E}=\) All Real Numbers \(\mathbb{R}\)

\(A = {@seta@} \)

Note: We write \(n(X)\) for the number of elements contained in the set \(X\). For example, \(n(A) = 6\).


(a) Let \(B\) be a set such that \( n(B)=4 \) and \( n(A \cap B)=3 \).
Find one possible set of elements for \(B\).

(b) Let \(C\) be a set such that \( n(C)=2 \) and \( C \subset B \)

Find one possible set of elements for \(C\).

(d) Let \(D\) be a set such that \( n(D)={@gg@} \) and \( n(D \cap C) = 1 \)

generalfeedback.text:
Worked Solution:

(a) \( n(B)=4 \) means that \(B\) is a set with 4 elements and \( n(A \cap B)=3 \) means that \(A\) and \(B\) have exactly 3 elements in common.
So \(B\) is a set with 3 elements from \(A\) and one element not from \(A\), for example:

\( B = \{ {@aa@} , {@cc@} , {@dd@} , 23 \} \)


(b) \( n(C)=2 \) means that \(C\) is a set with 2 elements and \( C \subset B \) means that \(C\) is a subset of \(B\), so every element of \(C\) is also in \(B\).
So \(C\) is a set with any 2 elements from your \(B\), for example:

\( C = \{ {@cc@}, 23 \} \)


(c) \(x \in A' \) means that \(x\) is an element of the complement of \(A\), \(x \in \mathbb{R} \setminus A\).
So, \(x\) is any real number that is not in \(A\), for example:

\( x= 359 \)


(d) \( n(D)={@gg@} \) means that \(D\) is a set with {@gg@} elements, and we know that \(C\) has 2 elements from (b).

\( n(D \cap C) =1 \) tells us that \(D\) and \(C\) have one element in common.

\( n(D \cup C) \), the union of \(D\) and \(C\), is the number of elements in either \(D\) or \(C\) - how many element in total?

You can draw a quick Venn Diagram if you aren't comfortable doing this in your head:

So the number of elements, all together (considering one is shared) is \( n(D \cup C) = {@gg+1@}\)
